{"response_text":"The number of active human foragers remains absolutely constant at 20 individuals across all 2,312 time steps of the simulation. The metric maintains a value of 20.0000 at the initial time step, throughout the entire temporal sequence, and at the final time step, exhibiting zero variance and no deviation from this value at any point. The mean, median, minimum, and maximum values of the forager count are all identically 20.0000.

Implications for decision makers:
The complete stability of the forager population establishes a constant baseline of human hunting pressure throughout the simulation period. This fixed anthropogenic predation pressure eliminates demographic stochasticity in the human agent population as a variable, allowing for precise assessment of megaherbivore population responses to sustained, unchanging hunting mortality. Decision makers can interpret resulting megaherbivore population trends as direct responses to consistent hunting pressure levels without confounding effects from changing human population dynamics or hunting effort fluctuations."}

